& v = \frac{9}{2 \cos 30^\circ}.
\end{align*}

Since \(\cos 30^\circ = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\), we have:
\[
v = \frac{9}{2 \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}} = \frac{9}{\sqrt{3}} = 3\sqrt{3} \, \text{m/s}
\]

\textbf{Kinetic Energy:}

Before the collision, the kinetic energy is:
\[
KE_{\text{initial}} = \frac{1}{2} m \times 9^2 = \frac{81m}{2}
\]

After the collision, the kinetic energy is:
\[
KE_{\text{final}} = 2 \times \frac{1}{2} m \times (3\sqrt{3})^2 = 2 \times \frac{1}{2} m \times 27 = 27m
\]

Since \(27m \neq \frac{81m}{2}\), the kinetic energy is not conserved in the collision process.

